fields.title: Pro Tips
fields.content:
Pro Tip #1.

Do More to Get More

All successful entrepreneurs are asked, when did you know you made it.

And they all have to think about it, no one has a defining moment.

That's because their success comes from gaining advantage day by day, little by little.

The things that successful and average entrepreneurs are not very different.

The successful ones simply Do more of it and they do it Every Day.

Over time they gain an advantage, it's only fair.

As long as you don't quit, what else can happen?

Tag your lazy friend that needs to hear this bellow.


Pro Tip #2

There is no Rocket Science

There are only things you know and things you don't know

fields.title: Year - Sat, Sep 29
fields.content:
The most important thing in the year journal are the goals.

Define the big goals here and then chunk them into smaller pieces in the month and/or week journals.

I personally often skip the monthly journal and use the week journal to chunk my goals into bite sized pieces.

The work I can do in a week is much easier for me to estimate than the whole month.

First, how to set your goals: The SMART strategy for goal setting.

S.M.A.R.T. stands for Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant and Time-bound.

  • Specific -Define the goal in detail, answer the questions like What, Where, When, How much etc.
  • ﻿Measurable - While pursuing the goal you must have a way to measure your progress
  • Achievable - Although the sky is the limit. Make sure to set achievable goals for the time constraint that you'll set for yourself.
  • Relevant - Make sure you are pursuing goals that actually improve your life.
  • Time-bound - Every goal must have a deadline, otherwise it is just a dream.

Let's apply the SMART strategy to the example of starting a blog and making it successful.

Vague﻿: Start a blog and make it successful

SMART﻿

Start a blog in the tech space, niche: VR and AR. Audience target is 5000 daily visitors by end of the year and to get featured in 2 major publications. To achieve this I will have these sub goals:

  • Set up the blog and make the design decent.
  • Become a better writer.
  • Make connections in the industry and develop social media presence.
  • Become great at SEO

Feel free to remove all the above, you can always find it in our knowledge base documents. The default yearly template begins bellow this line:

Start of year: Goals

Goal 1

    Description: (Define the specificity of the goal, What, Why, How, How much)

    How will I measure it: 

    Deadline: 

Goal 2

    Description: (Define the specificity of the goal, What, Why, How, How much)

    How will I measure it: 

    Deadline: 


End of Year: Reflection

What lessons did you learn in the past year?


What mistakes did you make and how will you make sure you do not repeat them?


What was the best thing you did all year, the most beneficial or the most fun?


Your goals, did you overachieve or underachieve. Did they improve your life, how?

fields.content:
The most important thing in the year journal are the goals.

Define the big goals here and then chunk them into smaller pieces in the month and/or week journals.

I personally often skip the monthly journal and only use the week journal to chunk my goals into bite sized pieces.

The work I can do in a week is much easier for me to estimate than the whole month.

First, how to set your goals: The SMART strategy for goal setting.

S.M.A.R.T. stands for Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant and Time-bound.

  • Specific -Define the goal in detail, answer the questions like What, Where, When, How much etc.
  • ﻿Measurable - While pursuing the goal you must have a way to measure your progress
  • Achievable - Although the sky is the limit. Make sure to set achievable goals for the time constraint that you'll set for yourself.
  • Relevant - Make sure you are pursuing goals that actually improve your life.
  • Time-bound - Every goal must have a deadline, otherwise it is just a dream.

Let's apply the SMART strategy to the example of starting a blog and making it successful.

Vague﻿: Start a blog and make it successful

SMART﻿

Start a blog in the tech space, niche: VR and AR. Audience target is 5000 daily visitors by end of the year and to get featured in 2 major publications. To achieve this I will have these sub goals:

  • Set up the blog and make the design decent.
  • Become a better writer.
  • Make connections in the industry and develop social media presence.
  • Become great at SEO

Feel free to remove all the above, you can always find it in our knowledge base documents. The default yearly template begins bellow this line:

fields.title: The War of Art
fields.content:
1. Your time is spent in the dark, the unknown, the place of infinite potential and disaster.

2. There are no limits to your successes and failures.

3. It can start with utility but it mustn't end there. The piece of work should inspire people. Just by using your software they should be inspired to be productive, be the best version of themselves, pay attention to details, maintain discipline, never settle and all that good stuff.

Chapter: 1
3 things I've learned
  • Your body and brain will lie to you

Knowing is not enough, you must apply

  1. I will run three times a week
  2. Fast every day
  3. Seek and Recognize the uncomfortable situations in life and use them to break out of homestasis

fields.content:
Book summary: Breaking Out Of Homeostasis

Chapter: 1
3 things I've learned
  • Your body and brain will lie to you
  • Two modes, create or consume
  • Must reach a pain threshold then go past it

Knowing is not enough, you must apply

Top three things I will implement in my life
  1. I will run three times a week
  2. Fast every day
  3. Seek and Recognize the uncomfortable situations in life and use them to break out of homestasis

fields.title: Best Practices
fields.content:
The Best Practices template consists of the following sections:

  • Basic 80/20 activities - the 20% most important activities that will give you 80% of the results
  • Specialist activities - these are activities to get special results, one step further from the basics above.
  • Common mistakes - list of common mistakes everybody tends to make. List them so you remember them. Keep this list updated when you discover new ones.


Example: Fitness Best Practices


Basic 80/20 activities:


Nutrition

  • Eliminate or minimize sugar
  • Eliminate or minimize white flour
  • Eat at least one salad per day
  • Minimize eating any food with long shelf life

Fitness

  • Move more, go on walks every day
  • Gym: focus on compound movements
  • Gym: Progressive overload, this means track your weights and make sure you are progressing over time


Specialist activities


Goal: Getting bellow 12% body fat, visible abs.

Nutrition:

  • Start to count calories
  • Maintain 300-500 calorie deficit every day
  • Eat more protein

Fitness:

  • Do cardio 3 times per week
  • Gym: perform less sets and repetitions but with heavier weight (this helps preserve muscle)


Common mistakes


  • ﻿Too much snacking between meals
  • Drinking beverages with hidden sugars
  • Eating foods with "0% fat" or "0% sugar"
  • Eating "healthy" deserts that still have too many calories
  • Not training hard enough, see https://leangains.com/fuckarounditis/
  • Not tracking progress with weights
  • Doing too much accessory work while neglecting the compound movements
